<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a QR code?", answer: "A QR code (Quick Response code) is a two-dimensional barcode that stores information in a matrix of black and white squares. It was invented in 1994 by Denso Wave, a subsidiary of Toyota, to track automotive parts during manufacturing. Unlike traditional barcodes that store data in one dimension, QR codes encode data both horizontally and vertically, allowing them to store significantly more information in a compact space." },
  { question: "What types of data can a QR code contain?", answer: "QR codes can encode various types of data including plain text, website URLs, email addresses, phone numbers, Wi-Fi credentials, geographic coordinates, calendar events, and contact information (vCard). The maximum capacity depends on the encoding mode: up to 7,089 numeric characters, 4,296 alphanumeric characters, or 2,953 bytes of binary data. For most practical purposes, short URLs and text under a few hundred characters work best." },
  { question: "How do QR code error correction levels work?", answer: "QR codes include Reed-Solomon error correction that allows the code to be read even if part of it is damaged or obscured. There are four error correction levels: L (Low, recovers 7% of data), M (Medium, recovers 15%), Q (Quartile, recovers 25%), and H (High, recovers 30%). Higher correction levels make the code more resilient but also increase its physical size because more redundant data modules are needed." },
  { question: "Are QR codes safe to scan?", answer: "QR codes themselves are not inherently dangerous, but they can link to malicious websites or trigger unwanted actions. Always check the URL preview before visiting a link from a scanned QR code. Most modern smartphone cameras and QR reader apps show the URL before navigating to it. Be cautious with QR codes found in public places, as attackers may place fraudulent codes over legitimate ones, a technique known as QR code phishing or 'quishing'." },
  { question: "Do QR codes expire?", answer: "Static QR codes, like the ones generated by this tool, never expire. The data is encoded directly in the pattern of squares and remains readable for as long as the physical code is intact. Dynamic QR codes, offered by some commercial platforms, use a redirect URL that the provider controls and may stop working if the service is discontinued or the subscription lapses. Static QR codes are permanent and free." },
  { question: "Can I generate Wi-Fi, contact, or SMS QR codes?", answer: "Yes. Use the format tabs above the input field to pick Text/URL, Wi-Fi, Contact (vCard), SMS, or Location. Wi-Fi QR codes let someone join your network by scanning — the phone reads the SSID, password, and encryption type and offers to connect. Contact QR codes encode a vCard that adds a name, phone, email, and website to the phone's address book in one scan. SMS QR codes open the messaging app with the number and an optional prefilled body. Location QR codes open the coordinates in the device's maps application." }
]) %>

